# machine.pins — per-machine version overrides

> THIS IS AN EXAMPLE TEMPLATE. Copy to `machine.pins.md` (without `.example`), then edit. The real file is gitignored.

## Why this layer exists

`what/standard/pins.md` is the canonical reference. This file lets operators override pins on machines that need a different Spacemacs SHA, Emacs version, or tooling configuration than the published commons.

Common reasons:

- Operator's macOS is on an older release that needs Emacs 28 instead of 29
- Operator on an air-gapped machine that uses a vendored clone of Spacemacs at a different SHA
- Operator on Linux with system Emacs at a different version than what `what/standard/pins.md` recommends

## Override format

| Pin | Override value | Reason |
|-----|----------------|--------|
| Spacemacs SHA | (set to a different SHA than standard) | (why) |
| Emacs minimum | (e.g., 28.2 instead of 29.0) | (why) |
| Tooling | e.g., use `mdfind` instead of `fd` | (why) |

## Override consequence

`skill_install` reads `what/standard/pins.md` first, then layers `what/local/machine.pins.md` (this file) on top. Mismatches between the merged pin and the host get reported but DON'T abort if this file explicitly overrides.

The override is logged to `deploy/<hostname>/<utc>.md` so the publish-clean check (Phase 6 sanitization scan) can verify only standard pins are used in published artifacts.
